<Description><![CDATA[Parts per hour for last 24 hours. Demonstrates DINT arrays.]]></Description>
</Tag>
<Tag Name="ShiftReportData" TagType="Base" DataType="REAL" Dimensions="8" Radix="Float" Constant="false" ExternalAccess="Read/Write">
<Description><![CDATA[Shift report data array (8 REAL values)]]></Description>
</Tag>

<!-- === Constants (immutable values) === -->
<Tag Name="MAX_PARTS_PER_BATCH" TagType="Base" DataType="DINT" Radix="Decimal" Constant="true" ExternalAccess="Read Only">
<Description><![CDATA[Constant: maximum batch size]]></Description>
<Data Format="L5K"><![CDATA[1000]]></Data>
<Data Format="Decorated"><DataValue DataType="DINT" Radix="Decimal" Value="1000"/></Data>
</Tag>
<Tag Name="SECONDS_PER_HOUR" TagType="Base" DataType="REAL" Radix="Float" Constant="true" ExternalAccess="Read Only">
<Description><![CDATA[Constant: 3600.0 seconds per hour]]></Description>
<Data Format="L5K"><![CDATA[3600.0]]></Data>
<Data Format="Decorated"><DataValue DataType="REAL" Radix="Float" Value="3600.0"/></Data>
</Tag>
</Tags>

<!-- ============================================================
     PROGRAMS
     Each program contains its own local tags and routines.
     ============================================================ -->
<Programs Use="Context">

<!-- ===== PROGRAM 1: MainProgram ===== -->
<Program Use="Target" Name="MainProgram" TestEdits="false" MainRoutineName="MainRoutine" Disabled="false" UseAsFolder="false">
<Description><![CDATA[Main program - orchestrates all subroutines. MainRoutine is the entry point.]]></Description>

<!-- Program-Scoped Tags (visible only within MainProgram) -->
<Tags Use="Context">
<Tag Name="ProgramOnlyFlag" TagType="Base" DataType="BOOL" Radix="Decimal" Constant="false" ExternalAccess="Read/Write">
<Description><![CDATA[This tag is ONLY visible inside MainProgram. Demonstrates program scope vs controller scope.]]></Description>
</Tag>
<Tag Name="LoopCounter" TagType="Base" DataType="DINT" Radix="Decimal" Constant="false" ExternalAccess="Read/Write">
<Description><![CDATA[Program-scoped counter]]></Description>
</Tag>
</Tags>

<Routines Use="Context">

<!-- ===== MainRoutine: Entry point, calls all subroutines ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="MainRoutine" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[MAIN ROUTINE - Entry point called every scan. Demonstrates JSR (Jump to Subroutine) to organize code into logical modules. Each JSR calls one concept-specific subroutine. JSR input parameters pass data INTO the subroutine; return parameters pass data BACK.]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 1: BIT LOGIC ==========
JSR to Bit_Logic routine. 0 input parameters, 0 return parameters.
This routine handles all boolean/bit-level operations.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JSR(Bit_Logic,0,0);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 2: TIMERS & COUNTERS ==========
JSR to Timers_Counters routine. Demonstrates timer/counter instructions.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JSR(Timers_Counters,0,0);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 3: MATH & COMPARE ==========
JSR to Math_Compare routine. Covers arithmetic, comparison, and compute.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JSR(Math_Compare,0,0);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 4: MOVE & DATA HANDLING ==========
JSR to Move_Data routine. MOV, COP, CPS, CLR, and indirect addressing.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JSR(Move_Data,0,0);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 5: PROGRAM CONTROL ==========
JSR to Program_Control routine. JMP/LBL, FOR/NXT, conditional execution.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JSR(Program_Control,0,0);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="5" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 6: MOTOR CONTROL via AOI ==========
Instantiates the aoiMotorStarter AOI for the conveyor motor.
Parameters: Start, Stop, FaultReset, FeedbackRun, Overload, FeedbackTimeout, Running, Faulted, Status
This is how you REUSE logic - the same AOI block works for any motor.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[aoiMotorStarter(ConveyorMotor,StartPB,StopPB,ResetPB,ConveyorRun,EmergencyStop,2000,ConveyorRun,AlarmLatched,ConveyorMotor);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="6" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 7: MOTOR CONTROL AOI REUSE ==========
Same AOI, different motor (cooling fan). Demonstrates AOI reusability -
one definition, infinite instances, each with independent data.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[aoiMotorStarter(FanMotor,StartPB,StopPB,ResetPB,PartSensor,EmergencyStop,1500,ConveyorRun,AlarmLatched,FanMotor);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="7" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[========== SECTION 8: CALL STRUCTURED TEXT ROUTINE ==========
JSR to a Structured Text routine. Shows that Ladder can call ST routines
and vice versa. Different languages, same program.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JSR(Structured_Text_Demo,0,0);]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>

<!-- ===== Routine: Bit_Logic ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Bit_Logic" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[BIT LOGIC CONCEPTS: XIC (Examine If Closed / NO contact), XIO (Examine If Open / NC contact), OTE (Output Energize / coil), OTL (Output Latch), OTU (Output Unlatch), ONS (One Shot Rising), OSF (One Shot Falling), OSR (One Shot Rising with storage). Branches [ ] for OR logic. Series for AND logic.]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Seal-in Circuit (Start/Stop Pattern)
XIC = normally-open contact (TRUE when tag=1). XIO = normally-closed contact (TRUE when tag=0).
This rung: if StartPB=1, energize SystemReady. SystemReady contact in parallel "seals in"
so it stays on even after StartPB releases. StopPB (XIO) breaks the seal.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(StartPB)[XIC(SystemReady),XIC(StartPB)]XIO(StopPB)XIO(EmergencyStop)XIC(SystemPowered)OTE(SystemReady);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Latch/Unlatch (OTL/OTU)
OTL = Output Latch: sets tag to 1 and holds it, even if rung goes false.
OTU = Output Unlatch: sets tag to 0.
Unlike OTE, OTL/OTU retain state across scans without a seal-in branch.
Here: EmergencyStop latches AlarmLatched ON. It stays ON until ResetPB unlatches it.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(EmergencyStop)OTL(AlarmLatched);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Unlatch (OTU) - resets the latched alarm.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(ResetPB)OTU(AlarmLatched);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: One-Shot Rising (ONS)
ONS = Output is TRUE for exactly ONE scan when the preceding logic transitions FALSE->TRUE.
Storage bit (PartDetectedONS) tracks previous state. Output (MachineActive) pulses for 1 scan.
Used for: triggering actions on edges, avoiding repeated execution.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(PartSensor)ONS(PartDetectedONS)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Series Contacts = AND Logic
All contacts in series must be TRUE for output to energize.
GateClosed=1 AND (EmergencyStop=0) AND SystemReady=1 AND MachineActive=1 -> CycleActive=1]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(GateClosed)XIO(EmergencyStop)XIC(SystemReady)XIC(MachineActive)OTE(CycleActive);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="5" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Parallel Branches = OR Logic
Brackets [ ] create parallel branches. At least one branch TRUE = rung TRUE.
ManualMode=1 OR AutoMode=1 -> MachineActive=1]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[[XIC(ManualMode),XIC(AutoMode)]OTE(MachineActive);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="6" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Combined Series + Parallel = Complex Logic
(SystemReady AND (ManualMode=1 OR AutoMode=1)) -> Process allowed.
Outer XIC/XIO are in series with the parallel branch group.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(SystemReady)[XIC(ManualMode),XIC(AutoMode)]OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="7" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Multiple Outputs on Same Rung
One rung condition can control multiple outputs. All energize simultaneously.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)OTE(ConveyorRun)OTL(AlarmLatched);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="8" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: XIO as Safety Check
XIO(EmergencyStop) = TRUE when E-Stop is NOT pressed (normal state).
This is safety convention: use NC contacts for safety devices so a broken wire
(which reads as 0/open) also triggers the safety condition.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIO(EmergencyStop)XIC(SystemPowered)OTE(ConveyorRun);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="9" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Negation / Debounce Pattern
XIO on a timer.DN bit creates a "NOT timed out" condition.
This rung is TRUE when CycleActive=1 AND InspectionDelay has NOT finished (is still timing).
Useful for: "while waiting" conditions, "not yet" guards.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleActive)XIO(InspectionDelay.DN)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>

<!-- ===== Routine: Timers_Counters ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Timers_Counters" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[TIMER & COUNTER CONCEPTS: TON (Timer On Delay), TOF (Timer Off Delay), RTO (Retentive Timer On), CTU (Count Up), CTD (Count Down), RES (Reset). Timer bits: .EN (enabled), .TT (timing), .DN (done). .PRE (preset), .ACC (accumulator). Counter bits: .CU (count up enable), .CD (count down enable), .DN (done), .OV (overflow), .UN (underflow).]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: TON - Timer On Delay
When rung is TRUE, timer begins counting. .DN bit goes TRUE when .ACC >= .PRE.
Preset = 2000ms. The timer resets to 0 when rung goes FALSE.
Used for: "wait 2 seconds before starting inspection after part detected".]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(PartSensor)TON(InspectionDelay,2000,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: TON - Inspection Window
While InspectionDelay.DN=1 AND PartSensor=1, run a 500ms window timer.
This creates a precise measurement window for weight reading.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionDelay.DN)XIC(PartSensor)TON(InspectionWindow,500,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: TOF - Timer Off Delay
TOF starts timing when rung goes FALSE (falling edge). Output is TRUE while timing.
Use case: keep conveyor running for 3 seconds after part clears the sensor,
so the next part can advance.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIO(PartSensor)TOF(ConveyorRunOff,3000,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: RTO - Retentive Timer On
RTO accumulates time across multiple TRUE periods. Does NOT reset when rung goes FALSE.
Must use RES instruction to reset. Use case: total shift run time, across many cycles.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleActive)RTO(ShiftRunTime,28800000,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CTU - Count Up Counter
Each FALSE->TRUE transition of the rung increments .ACC by 1.
.DN = TRUE when .ACC >= .PRE. Preset=999999 means "count essentially unlimited".
Use case: total parts ever processed.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)CTU(TotalPartCounter,999999,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="5" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CTD - Count Down Counter
Each FALSE->TRUE transition decrements .ACC by 1.
Preset sets starting count. .DN = TRUE when .ACC <= 0.
Use case: countdown from batch size, signal when batch is complete.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)CTD(BatchRemaining,100,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="6" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CTU with Conditional Count
Only counts when InspectionWindow.DN=1 AND the calculated deviation is within tolerance.
This counts GOOD parts only.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)XIC(ProgramOnlyFlag)CTU(GoodPartCounter,999999,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="7" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: RES - Reset Timer/Counter
RES clears .ACC to 0 and resets all status bits (.DN, .TT, .EN).
Used here: reset shift timer and counters at start of new shift.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(ResetPB)[RES(ShiftRunTime),RES(TotalPartCounter),RES(GoodPartCounter)];]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="8" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Timer Status Bits in Logic
Using .DN (Done), .TT (Timing), .EN (Enabled) as conditions.
.MOD = timer is timing (TT). Used to light a "timing" indicator.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionDelay.TT)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="9" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Counter Status Bits
TotalPartCounter.DN goes TRUE when ACC >= 999999 (overflow warning).
Use .OV (overflow) for safety - stop if counter rolls over.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(TotalPartCounter.OV)OTL(AlarmLatched);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="10" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Combined Timer + Counter
When cycle finishes, start a 1-second pulse timer. Each pulse increments a counter.
This effectively counts "how many seconds the cycle was complete" - a basic
runtime accumulator pattern.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)TON(HealthCheckTimer,1000,?)XIC(HealthCheckTimer.DN)CTU(TotalPartCounter,999999,?);]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>

<!-- ===== Routine: Math_Compare ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Math_Compare" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[MATH & COMPARISON CONCEPTS: ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, CPT (Compute), MOD (Modulo), SQR (Square Root), ABS (Absolute Value), MOV for constants, EQU, NEQ, GRT, LES, GEQ, LEQ, LIM (Limit Test), CMP (Comparison).]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: ADD - Addition
ADD(SourceA, SourceB, Destination). Destination = SourceA + SourceB.
Here: convert raw integer weight (grams*100) to REAL by dividing by 100.0.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)ADD(PartWeightRaw,0,CalculatedResult);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: DIV - Division
DIV(SourceA, SourceB, Destination). Destination = SourceA / SourceB.
Here: PartWeight = PartWeightRaw / 100.0 (convert centigrams to grams).]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)DIV(PartWeightRaw,100.0,PartWeight);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: SUB - Subtraction
Destination = GoodParts - RejectParts. This gives net good parts.
Negative result means more rejects than good parts.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)SUB(GoodParts,RejectParts,CalculatedResult);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: MUL - Multiplication
ProductionRate = PartCount * SECONDS_PER_HOUR / ShiftRunTime.ACC.
Gives parts-per-hour rate. This is a basic OEE performance metric.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(HealthCheckTimer.DN)MUL(PartCount,SECONDS_PER_HOUR,ProductionRate);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: DIV with REAL result
ProductionRate = ProductionRate / ShiftRunTime.ACC.
Completing the parts-per-hour calculation. Note: Division by zero
causes a minor fault if ShiftRunTime.ACC = 0. Guard with GRT check first.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(HealthCheckTimer.DN)GRT(ShiftRunTime.ACC,0)DIV(ProductionRate,ShiftRunTime.ACC,ProductionRate);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="5" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CPT - Compute (Expression-Based Math)
CPT lets you write complex math as a single text expression.
Here: OEE_Availability = (RunTime / PlannedTime) but simplified as example.
Expression: (PartCount * TargetWeight) / (ShiftTarget * TargetWeight)
This evaluates the entire formula in one instruction instead of chaining ADD/MUL/DIV.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(HealthCheckTimer.DN)CPT(OEE_Availability,(PartCount * TargetWeight) / (ShiftTarget * TargetWeight));]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="6" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: MOD - Modulo (Remainder)
MOD(SourceA, SourceB, Destination). Destination = remainder of A / B.
Here: check if PartCount is even (MOD 2 = 0) or odd (MOD 2 = 1).
Useful for: alternating actions, round-robin scheduling, parity checks.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)MOD(PartCount,2,CalculatedResult);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="7" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: SQR - Square Root
SQR(Source, Destination). Destination = sqrt(Source).
Example use: statistical standard deviation calculation step.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(HealthCheckTimer.DN)SQR(PartWeight,DeviationValue);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="8" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: ABS - Absolute Value
ABS(Source, Destination). Destination = |Source|.
Here: calculate absolute deviation from target weight.
ABS(PartWeight - TargetWeight) = how far off the weight is, regardless of over/under.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)SUB(PartWeight,TargetWeight,DeviationValue)ABS(DeviationValue,DeviationValue);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="9" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: EQU - Equal Comparison
EQU(SourceA, SourceB). TRUE when A == B.
Here: check if CalculatedResult equals exactly 0 (even part count).]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[EQU(CalculatedResult,0)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="10" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: NEQ - Not Equal Comparison
NEQ(SourceA, SourceB). TRUE when A != B.
Here: flag when part weight differs from target (always true in practice).]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[NEQ(PartWeight,TargetWeight)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="11" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: GRT + LES - Range Check
GRT(SourceA, SourceB) = A > B. LES(SourceA, SourceB) = A < B.
Combined: GRT checks above max tolerance, LES checks below min.
This creates a "window comparator" - is weight within +/- tolerance?]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)GRT(DeviationValue,WeightTolerance)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="12" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: GEQ + LEQ - Inclusive Comparisons
GEQ = greater-than-or-equal. LEQ = less-than-or-equal.
Here: check if weight is within acceptable range [Target-5.0, Target+5.0].
Two separate comparisons yield two separate bits for detailed reporting.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)GEQ(PartWeight,TargetWeight)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="13" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: LIM - Limit Test
LIM(LowLimit, Test, HighLimit). TRUE if LowLimit <= Test <= HighLimit.
This is the single-instruction equivalent of the GEQ+LEQ pair above.
Much cleaner! Checks if PartWeight is between TargetWeight-5.0 and TargetWeight+5.0.
Note: LowLimit must be <= HighLimit, or LIM behaves as "outside" test.
Here we use CPT to compute the limits inline (not standard in all versions, shown for concept).]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[LIM(245.0,PartWeight,255.0)OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="14" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CMP - Comparison (Expression)
CMP lets you write any comparison expression. More flexible than individual instructions.
Expression: PartWeight > (TargetWeight + WeightTolerance)
This flags OVERWEIGHT parts. Combine with a LES expression for UNDERWEIGHT.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[CMP(PartWeight > (TargetWeight + WeightTolerance))OTE(ProgramOnlyFlag);]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>

<!-- ===== Routine: Move_Data ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Move_Data" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[MOVE & DATA HANDLING CONCEPTS: MOV (Move value), COP (Copy block), CPS (Synchronous Copy), CLR (Clear), indirect addressing with [index], UDT member access with dot notation.]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: MOV - Move Value
MOV(Source, Destination). Copies Source value into Destination.
Here: transfer PartCount to PartHistory[0].PartID on cycle complete.
Simple 1:1 value copy. Works with all atomic data types.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)MOV(PartCount,PartHistory[0].PartID);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: MOV with Constant
Store the current part weight into the UDT member CurrentPart.Weight.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)MOV(PartWeight,CurrentPart.Weight);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: COP - Copy Block (Length Specified)
COP(Source, Destination, Length). Copies Length elements from Source to Destination.
Here: copy all 8 values from ShiftReportData array to HourlyCount array.
Length is in DESTINATION elements. Both arrays must be same type.
WARNING: COP does NOT check data types. Copying DINT to REAL will produce garbage.
Use CPS (synchronous copy) for multi-element copies that must be consistent.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(ResetPB)COP(ShiftReportData[0],HourlyCount[0],8);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CPS - Synchronous Copy
CPS(Source, Destination, Length). Like COP but interrupts are disabled during copy.
Use CPS when copying multi-element data that could be modified by another task
or I/O update mid-copy. CPS guarantees atomic copy.
Here: copy inspection result into history array safely.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(InspectionWindow.DN)CPS(CurrentPart,PartHistory[0],1);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: CLR - Clear Value
CLR(Destination). Sets Destination to 0 (for numeric types).
Here: clear current part record at start of new cycle.
Cleaner than MOV(0, CurrentPart.Weight).]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleActive)CLR(CurrentPart.Weight);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="5" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: MOV with Indirect/Indexed Addressing
MOV(Source, Array[Index]). The [ForLoopIndex] is an indirect address.
As ForLoopIndex changes, different array elements are accessed.
This is how you iterate through arrays in ladder logic.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(HealthCheckTimer.DN)MOV(ProductionRate,ShiftReportData[ForLoopIndex]);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="6" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Copy UDT to UDT
COP between two UDT instances copies all members. Source and destination
must be the same UDT type. This is a "snapshot" of a part record.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(CycleComplete)COP(CurrentPart,PartHistory[0],1);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="7" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Fill Array with Constant
Use FLL (Fill) or COP from a constant tag to initialize an array.
Here: on reset, fill HourlyCount array with zeros using COP from a cleared DINT.
(Studio 5000 also has FLL instruction specifically for filling.)]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(ResetPB)CLR(HourlyCount[0]);]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>

<!-- ===== Routine: Program_Control ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Program_Control" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[PROGRAM CONTROL CONCEPTS: JMP (Jump to Label), LBL (Label), FOR/NXT (For-Next loop), JSR (Jump to Subroutine), RET (Return). These instructions alter the normal top-to-bottom scan order.]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: JMP/LBL - Unconditional Jump
JMP(LabelName) skips all rungs until LBL(LabelName).
This skips the FOR/NXT loop section entirely.
Useful for: debug sections that can be toggled on/off.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[JMP(SkipLoop);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: LBL - Label Target
This is the jump target for the JMP above. Everything between JMP and LBL is skipped.
Labels are string identifiers (up to 40 chars).]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[LBL(SkipLoop);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: Conditional JMP
When SkipSection=TRUE, jump over the next rungs to label DebugSkip.
This lets you conditionally enable/disable sections of code at runtime.
Useful for: maintenance mode, feature toggles, testing.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(SkipSection)JMP(DebugSkip);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[These rungs are skipped when SkipSection=TRUE. They would normally execute here.
In a real project, this is where optional debug/complex logic lives.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[NOP;]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: LBL for Conditional Jump Target]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[LBL(DebugSkip);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="5" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: FOR/NXT - For-Next Loop
FOR(IndexTag, InitialValue, FinalValue, StepSize). Repeats rungs until NXT.
The rungs between FOR and NXT execute repeatedly with IndexTag incrementing
from 0 to 23 by step 1. After NXT, execution continues to the next rung.

WARNING: FOR/NXT loops consume scan time. Large loops can cause scan overrun.
Always use a reasonable limit. The FOR instruction disables itself if index
exceeds final value.

Here: iterate through HourlyCount[0..23] and zero each element.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[FOR(ForLoopIndex,0,23,1)CLR(HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex])NXT;]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="6" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: FOR/NXT with Conditional Execution Inside Loop
Inside the FOR loop, check each HourlyCount element. If non-zero,
copy to ShiftReportData (accumulate report data).
The XIC(HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex]) only applies to the MOV, not the FOR/NXT.
The loop always iterates 24 times regardless of internal conditions.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[FOR(ForLoopIndex,0,23,1)GRT(HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex],0)ADD(HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex],ShiftReportData[ForLoopIndex],ShiftReportData[ForLoopIndex])NXT;]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="7" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[CONCEPT: RET - Return (Early Exit)
RET immediately exits this routine and returns to the calling JSR.
Here: if EmergencyStop is active, exit early - don't execute remaining logic.
Useful for: guard clauses that prevent execution in unsafe states.
Only works inside subroutines called via JSR, not in MainRoutine.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[XIC(EmergencyStop)RET();]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>

<!-- ===== Routine: Structured_Text_Demo ===== -->
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Structured_Text_Demo" Type="ST">
<Description><![CDATA[STRUCTURED TEXT CONCEPTS: The same logic concepts expressed in Structured Text (IEC 61131-3 ST language). Demonstrates IF/THEN/ELSE, CASE, FOR loops, assignments :=, function calls, and comments. ST is often preferred for complex math, string handling, and state machines.]]></Description>
<STContent>
<![CDATA[(* ============================================================
   STRUCTURED TEXT DEMONSTRATION
   Same concepts as the ladder routines, expressed in ST syntax.
   Language: IEC 61131-3 Structured Text
   Key syntax:
     :=      Assignment (like MOV)
     ;       Statement terminator
     IF...THEN...ELSIF...ELSE...END_IF   Conditional
     CASE...OF...END_CASE                Multi-way branch
     FOR...TO...BY...DO...END_FOR        Loop
     //      Single-line comment
     (* *)   Multi-line comment
   ============================================================ *)

// ----- BIT LOGIC in ST -----
// Seal-in circuit using IF/THEN
IF StartPB THEN
    SystemReady := 1;
END_IF;

IF StopPB OR EmergencyStop THEN
    SystemReady := 0;
END_IF;

// Latch/Unlatch emulation (ST has no native latch)
// OTL equivalent: set and hold
IF EmergencyStop THEN
    AlarmLatched := 1;
END_IF;

// OTU equivalent: clear
IF ResetPB THEN
    AlarmLatched := 0;
END_IF;

// One-shot detection (rising edge)
// Uses a static variable pattern: compare current vs previous
IF PartSensor AND NOT PartDetectedONS THEN
    PartDetectedONS := 1;   // One-shot pulse
ELSE
    PartDetectedONS := 0;
END_IF;

// AND / OR logic in ST
CycleActive := GateClosed AND NOT EmergencyStop AND SystemReady AND MachineActive;
MachineActive := ManualMode OR AutoMode;

// ----- TIMERS in ST -----
// TON - Timer On Delay
TONR(InspectionDelay);  // Note: timer calls vary by platform
// In Studio 5000 ST, timers are called as function blocks:
// TON(InspectionDelay, 2000);

// TOF - Timer Off Delay
// TOF(ConveyorRunOff, 3000);

// RTO - Retentive Timer
// RTO(ShiftRunTime, 28800000);

// ----- COUNTERS in ST -----
// CTU - Count Up
IF InspectionWindow.DN THEN
    CTU(TotalPartCounter, 999999);
END_IF;

// ----- MATH in ST -----
// ST excels at math - much cleaner than ladder for formulas
PartWeight := DINT_TO_REAL(PartWeightRaw) / 100.0;
DeviationValue := ABS(PartWeight - TargetWeight);

// OEE Calculation (complex formula in one expression)
OEE_Availability := (DINT_TO_REAL(PartCount) * TargetWeight) 
                  / (DINT_TO_REAL(ShiftTarget) * TargetWeight);

OEE_Performance := (DINT_TO_REAL(PartCount) * TargetWeight)
                 / (DINT_TO_REAL(ShiftTarget) * TargetWeight);

IF GoodParts > 0 THEN
    OEE_Quality := DINT_TO_REAL(GoodParts) 
                 / DINT_TO_REAL(GoodParts + RejectParts);
ELSE
    OEE_Quality := 0.0;
END_IF;

ProductionRate := (DINT_TO_REAL(PartCount) * 3600.0) 
                / DINT_TO_REAL(ShiftRunTime.ACC);

// Modulo (remainder) - check even/odd
IF (PartCount MOD 2) = 0 THEN
    // PartCount is even
    ProgramOnlyFlag := 1;
ELSE
    ProgramOnlyFlag := 0;
END_IF;

// ----- COMPARISONS in ST -----
// Same operators as ladder but inline
IF PartWeight = TargetWeight THEN
    // Exact match (rare in real world with floating point)
END_IF;

IF DeviationValue > WeightTolerance THEN
    // Part is out of tolerance - flag as reject
    CurrentPart.InspectionResult := 2;  // Fail
END_IF;

// LIM equivalent: range check
IF (PartWeight >= 245.0) AND (PartWeight <= 255.0) THEN
    CurrentPart.InspectionResult := 1;  // Pass
ELSE
    CurrentPart.InspectionResult := 3;  // Fail
END_IF;

// CMP equivalent: direct boolean expression
ProgramOnlyFlag := (PartWeight > (TargetWeight + WeightTolerance));

// ----- DATA HANDLING in ST -----
// MOV equivalent
PartHistory[0].PartID := PartCount;

// COP equivalent (array copy)
FOR i := 0 TO 7 DO
    HourlyCount[i] := PartHistory[i].PartID;  // Indirect array access
END_FOR;

// CLR equivalent
CurrentPart.Weight := 0.0;
CurrentPart.InspectionResult := 0;

// ----- PROGRAM CONTROL in ST -----
// IF/THEN/ELSE (conditional execution)
IF SkipSection THEN
    // Skip this entire block
ELSE
    // Execute normal logic
    FOR i := 0 TO 23 DO
        HourlyCount[i] := 0;  // Clear array
    END_FOR;
END_IF;

// CASE statement (multi-way branch) - cleaner than nested IFs
CASE CurrentPart.InspectionResult OF
    0:  // Pending
        ProgramOnlyFlag := 0;
    1:  // Pass
        GoodParts := GoodParts + 1;
    2, 3:  // Fail (Under or Over)
        RejectParts := RejectParts + 1;
    4:  // Fail Other
        RejectParts := RejectParts + 1;
END_CASE;

// FOR loop (same as FOR/NXT in ladder)
FOR ForLoopIndex := 0 TO 23 BY 1 DO
    HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex] := 0;
END_FOR;

// RET equivalent: EXIT or RETURN
IF EmergencyStop THEN
    RETURN;  // Exit routine immediately
END_IF;

// ----- FOR/NEXT loop with complex body -----
FOR ForLoopIndex := 0 TO 23 BY 1 DO
    IF HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex] > 0 THEN
        ShiftReportData[ForLoopIndex] := ShiftReportData[ForLoopIndex] 
                                       + DINT_TO_REAL(HourlyCount[ForLoopIndex]);
    END_IF;
END_FOR;

]]>
</STContent>
</Routine>

</Routines>
</Program>

<!-- ===== PROGRAM 2: Periodic_Calc (periodic task) ===== -->
<Program Use="Target" Name="Periodic_Calc" TestEdits="false" MainRoutineName="Periodic_Routine" Disabled="false" UseAsFolder="false">
<Description><![CDATA[Periodic calculation program - runs every 100ms regardless of continuous scan. Demonstrates periodic tasks, which are essential for PID loops, communications, and time-critical calculations.]]></Description>
<Tags Use="Context">
<Tag Name="ScanCounter" TagType="Base" DataType="DINT" Radix="Decimal" Constant="false" ExternalAccess="Read/Write">
<Description><![CDATA[Increments each periodic scan (every 100ms). Counts how many times this task has run.]]></Description>
</Tag>
<Tag Name="OEE_UpdateFlag" TagType="Base" DataType="BOOL" Radix="Decimal" Constant="false" ExternalAccess="Read/Write">
<Description><![CDATA[Flag set every 10 seconds (100 scans * 100ms) to trigger OEE update]]></Description>
</Tag>
</Tags>
<Routines Use="Context">
<Routine Use="Target" Name="Periodic_Routine" Type="RLL">
<Description><![CDATA[Runs every 100ms. Calculates real-time production metrics.]]></Description>
<RLLContent>

<Rung Number="0" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[Increment scan counter each execution (every 100ms)]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[ADD(ScanCounter,1,ScanCounter);]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="1" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[Every 100 scans (10 seconds), calculate production rate.
100 scans * 100ms = 10,000ms = 10 seconds. MOD 100 = 0 detects this interval.
This is how you create timed execution inside a periodic task.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[EQU(ScanCounter,100)[MOV(0,ScanCounter),MUL(PartCount,SECONDS_PER_HOUR,ProductionRate)];]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="2" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[Calculate OEE Quality metric: GoodParts / (GoodParts + RejectParts).
CPT with conditional guard: (GoodParts + RejectParts) must be > 0 to avoid division by zero.
If denominator is 0, OEE_Quality stays at its previous value.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[GRT(GoodParts,0)CPT(OEE_Quality,GoodParts / (GoodParts + RejectParts));]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="3" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[Calculate OEE Performance metric using compute expression.
PartCount / (ShiftTarget * (ShiftRunTime.ACC / 3600000.0))
This compares actual rate to ideal rate based on elapsed time.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[CPT(OEE_Performance,PartCount / (ShiftTarget * (ShiftRunTime.ACC / 3600000.0)));]]></Text>
</Rung>

<Rung Number="4" Type="N">
<Comment><![CDATA[MOV production metrics into shift report array for trending.
Index wraps at 8 elements (0-7), looping every 80 seconds.]]></Comment>
<Text><![CDATA[MOV(ProductionRate,ShiftReportData[ScanCounter]);]]></Text>
</Rung>

</RLLContent>
</Routine>
</Routines>
</Program>

</Programs>

<!-- ============================================================
     TASKS
     Define how programs execute.
     ============================================================ -->
<Tasks Use="Context">

<!-- Continuous Task: runs MainProgram in an infinite loop -->
<Task Use="Target" Name="MainTask" Type="CONTINUOUS" Priority="10" Watchdog="500" DisableUpdateOutputs="false" InhibitTask="false">
<Description><![CDATA[Continuous task - runs MainProgram repeatedly as fast as the processor allows. This is the default task type. Every scan: read inputs -> execute logic -> write outputs -> housekeeping. Watchdog = 500ms (if scan exceeds this, major fault).]]></Description>
<ScheduledPrograms>
<ScheduledProgram Name="MainProgram"/>
</ScheduledPrograms>
</Task>

<!-- Periodic Task: runs Periodic_Calc every 100ms -->
<Task Use="Target" Name="PeriodicTask" Type="PERIODIC" Rate="100" Priority="5" Watchdog="100" DisableUpdateOutputs="false" InhibitTask="false">
<Description><![CDATA[Periodic task - executes Periodic_Calc every 100ms. Higher priority (5 < 10) so it interrupts MainTask. Use periodic tasks for: PID loops, motion control, communications, regular calculations. Rate=100ms, Watchdog=100ms (must complete within one period).]]></Description>
<ScheduledPrograms>
<ScheduledProgram Name="Periodic_Calc"/>
</ScheduledPrograms>
</Task>

</Tasks>

<!-- ============================================================
     TRENDS
     Configure data logging for visualization.
     ============================================================ -->
<Trends Use="Context">
<Trend Use="Target" Name="ProductionTrend" SampleMode="Periodic" SamplePeriod="1000" SamplePointsMaximum="3600" Enable="true" SampleOnChange="false" SampleOutputMask="0000_0000">
<Description><![CDATA[Trends plot tag values over time. This one samples ProductionRate every 1000ms, storing up to 3600 points (1 hour). Open in Studio 5000: Controller Organizer > Trends > ProductionTrend.]]></Description>
<Tag Name="ProductionRate"/>
<Tag Name="PartCount"/>
<Tag Name="GoodParts"/>
</Trend>

<Trend Use="Target" Name="OEE_Trend" SampleMode="Periodic" SamplePeriod="5000" SamplePointsMaximum="720" Enable="true" SampleOnChange="false" SampleOutputMask="0000_0000">
<Description><![CDATA[OEE metrics trend - sampled every 5 seconds, 720 points = 1 hour of data.]]></Description>
<Tag Name="OEE_Availability"/>
<Tag Name="OEE_Performance"/>
<Tag Name="OEE_Quality"/>
</Trend>
</Trends>

<CST MasterID="0"/>
<WallClockTime LocalTimeAdjustment="0" TimeZone="0"/>
<DataLogs/>
<TimeSynchronize Priority1="128" Priority2="128" PTPEnable="false"/>
</Controller>
</RSLogix5000Content>
